  <h3 id="1-old-style-serif-humanist-">1. Old Style Serif (Humanist)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Inspired by early calligraphy and handwriting from the Renaissance period.
    </li>
    <li>
      Features <strong>gentle curves</strong> and <strong>slanted stress</strong
      > (the thinnest part of the letter isn&apos;t perfectly vertical).
    </li>
    <li>
      The serifs themselves are <strong>bracketed</strong>, meaning they
      smoothly curve into the main strokes.
    </li>
    <li>Feels warm, classic, and highly readable.</li>
    <li><em>Examples</em>: Garamond, Caslon</li>
    <li>
      <strong>Best for</strong> Long form reading, editorial design, academic publications.
    </li>
    <img src="/typography/garamond.png" />
  </ul>
  <h3 id="2-transitional-serif">2. Transitional Serif</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Came about during the 18th century as a “bridge” between Old Style and
      Modern (Didone) serifs.
    </li>
    <li>
      Has <strong>sharper contrast</strong> between thick and thin strokes.
    </li>
    <li>
      The stress ( ) is more vertical than Old Style, and the serifs are <strong
        >less rounded</strong
      >.
    </li>
    <li>
      <em>Examples</em>: Baskerville and the all time popular Times New Roman
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Best for</strong> Formal invitations, upscale branding, elegant print
      design.
    </li>
    <img src="/typography/serif.png" />
  </ul>
  <h3 id="3-didone-serif-modern-">3. Didone Serif (Modern)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Born in the late 18th to early 19th century.</li>
    <li>
      <strong>Extreme contrast</strong> between thick and thin lines.
    </li>
    <li>
      Serifs are <strong>thin, flat, and unbracketed</strong>—giving a very
      crisp, high fashion look.
    </li>
    <li><em>Examples</em>: Bodoni, Didot</li>
    <li>
      <strong>Best for</strong>: Headlines, fashion magazines, luxury branding.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <h3 id="4-slab-serif">4. Slab Serif</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Thick, blocky serifs that are the same thickness as the letter strokes.
    </li>
    <li>Minimal or no contrast in stroke width.</li>
    <li>
      Gives a <strong>strong, sturdy, and modern</strong> feel—popular in advertising
      and posters.
    </li>
    <li><em>Examples</em>: Rockwell, Courier</li>
    <li>
      <strong>Best for</strong>: Posters, logos, tech branding, signage.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <h3 id="5-glyphic-serif">5. Glyphic Serif</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Inspired by carved stone inscriptions, especially in ancient Roman
      monuments.
    </li>
    <li>
      The serifs are more like <strong>flared stroke endings</strong> rather than
      separate “feet.”
    </li>
    <li>Often feels formal, classic, and timeless.</li>
    <li><em>Examples</em>: Trajan</li>
    <li>
      <strong>Best for</strong>: Movie titles, formal branding, certificates.
    </li>
  </ul>
